description:
The Government's efforts to once again impose Hindi in the south - though the National Education Policy - seems to be backfiring in an ugly manner.... first Tamil Nadu and Karnataka - now regional partied in Maharashtra are using the language issue as a counter to 'Hindi Imposition' - this is often now taking a violent turn. 
Not the first time that language has led to violence - all the more reason that the Govt and regional parties stop fanning the flames of this sensitive issue .... but can all sides reach a consensus on what will be a common link language for India???

comments.text:
Tamil Nadu foresaw these challenges even at the time of independence. They expressed concerns that people from the South might not be treated equally by those from the North and even considered the idea of a separate country. Unfortunately, some of those fears are proving to be valid today.

Why is it that people from the South are expected to learn Hindi, while many in the North show no willingness to educate themselves? Instead, many blindly follow caste-driven and religious political agendas.

Its even more hypocritical when some claim that English is a foreign language and insist on promoting Hindi, while ignoring the fact that languages like Tamil, Telugu, Kannada, and Malayalam are much older than Hindi.

To those who demand Hindi: why do you educate your children in English-medium schools? Why do you use English for mobile phones, electronics, banking, and IT? If English is so problematic, why is it the backbone of your professional and digital life?

If people dont change their mindset and embrace equal respect for all languages and cultures, we may end up facing a real divide between North and South India.
